			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">This project will show how historical information traditionally used in actuarial calculations can be combined with forward-looking information contained in financial market prices. The two sorts of information are currently being combined in many practical applications of risk management but often in inconsistent ways. This leads to biases in risk assessment which in turn can lead to bad decisions -- either excessive risk-taking or excessive conservatism depending upon the context. For example, suppose in history lenders have lost 100% on defaulted loans in an emerging market because of poor bankruptcy laws. If bankruptcy laws have improved subsequently, making loans evaluations based on past experience might lead lenders to refuse credit to good borrowers. Market information incorporated in stock, bonds and other financial prices will be forward looking and will take into account the changes that have taken place in the economy. The question is how can the relevant forward looking information be gleaned from the prices?Building on developments in the field of econometric analysis of financial derivatives we will develop a consistent methodology for two important areas of risk assessment where the actuarial profession is active: credit risk assessment and the management of pension assets and liabilities. We will show how information on default frequencies and defaulted loan recovery rates can be built into models that calculate the fair price of a loan. Conversely, we will show how information contained in stock prices or credit default swap rates can be used to update estimates of a borrowers probability of default and thus the borrower's credit rating. When applied to pensions, these tools will be directly relevant to important policy problems such as the dealing with stock market volatility in determining pension fund solvency. Furthermore, our project will show how credit quality of a pension fund depends upon the credit quality of the sponsoring company and vice versa. We will also show how the methodology can be used in two cutting-edge risk management problems faced by financial institutions: operational risk and integrating risks for the purposes of enterprise risk management.The key idea in the project is to recognize that when looking forward to uncertain events the market assigns a premium</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
